\f1\b  January 25, 1736. \
\

\f0\b0 \uc0\u55356 \u56812 \u55356 \u56807 
\f1\b  On this day, Joseph-Louis Lagrange
\f2\b0  (born 
\f1\b Giuseppe Luigi Lagrangia
\f2\b0 ) was born. He was an Italian {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematician"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 mathematician}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Astronomer"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 astronomer}}, later naturalized French who made significant contributions to the fields of {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_analysis"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 analysis}}, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Number_theory"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 number theory}}, and both {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Classical_mechanics"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 classical}} and {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Celestial_mechanics"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 celestial mechanics}}.\cb1 \
\cb3 In 1766, on the recommendation of Swiss {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leonhard_Euler"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Leonhard Euler}} and French {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jean_le_Rond_d%27Alembert"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 d'Alembert}}, Lagrange succeeded Euler as the director of mathematics at the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prussian_Academy_of_Sciences"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Prussian Academy of Sciences}} in Berlin, {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Prussia"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Prussia}}, where he stayed for over twenty years, producing volumes of work and winning several prizes of the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/French_Academy_of_Sciences"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 French Academy of Sciences}}. Lagrange's treatise on {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Analytical_mechanics"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 analytical mechanics}} ({\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/M%C3%A9canique_analytique"}}{\fldrslt 
\f3\i \cf4 M\'e9canique analytique}}), written in Berlin and first published in 1788, offered the most comprehensive treatment of classical mechanics since {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isaac_Newton"}}{\fldrslt \cf5 Newton}} and formed a basis for the development of mathematical physics in the nineteenth century.\
\cb1 \
\cb3 In 1787, at age 51, he moved from Berlin to Paris and became a member of the French Academy of Sciences. He remained in France until the end of his life. He was instrumental in the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_the_metric_system"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 decimalisation}} in {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/French_First_Republic"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Revolutionary France}}, became the first professor of analysis at the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%89cole_Polytechnique"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 \'c9cole Polytechnique}} upon its opening in 1794, was a founding member of the {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bureau_des_Longitudes"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Bureau des Longitudes}}, and became {\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/S%C3%A9nat_conservateur"}}{\fldrslt \cf4 Senator}} in 1799.\
\
